  "unmapped_findings": [
    "DSC phase transformation temperatures: 0Be steel 1278.8 °C; Be addition reduces transformation temperature by approximately 120 °C (0.5Be causes a sharp drop, 1.0Be slightly lower by ~1 °C, 1.5Be by about 5 °C).",
    "The engineering stress-strain curves (Fig. 10) show that 0.5Be has the highest elongation (40.47%) and a high work hardening rate after an initial drop.",
    "Fracture morphology (Fig. 12): 0Be and 0.5Be show ductile dimples; with increasing Be content, cleavage planes and quasi-cleavage features appear, indicating a mixed ductile-brittle fracture in 1.0Be and 1.5Be steels.",
    "Addition of Be leads to lattice contraction (unlike Al which expands the lattice), so density reduction is not as strong as expected; the measured densities (6.47–6.29 g/cm3) are higher than theoretical predictions.",
    "In the as-cast 1.5Be steel, AlFe3 intermetallic was identified by TEM (Fig. 4).",
    "The 0.5Be rolled steel achieved a strength-ductility product (UST × TE) of about 45.5 GPa% with the lowest density among the series, defining a new space in the density-strength-ductility map."
  ]
